The actual function performed by the POST method is determined by the
server and is usually dependent on the Request-URI. The posted entity
is subordinate to that URI in the same way that a file is subordinate
to a directory containing it, a news article is subordinate to a
newsgroup to which it is posted, or a record is subordinate to a
database.
&quot;&quot;&quot;

I don&#39;t see where this imply MoST... your proposed is based on Mime, not
HTTP, to imply how to interact with the resource...


&gt; &gt; These are application level specificities, while Rest is
&gt; &gt; communication/interaction level.
&gt; 
&gt; MoST addresses the same level as ReST.
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; You can define a common way to express
&gt; &gt; rules and restrictions of your application, as you can define a generic
&gt; &gt; container &quot;super-type&quot;, with the corresponding behaviours, but I thing
&gt; &gt; that is out of the scope of ReST...
&gt; 
&gt; HTTP completely specifies the meaning of HTTP methods with respect to HTTP 
&gt; resources.  If you are defining different meanings for these methods you 
&gt; are violating HTTP.  MoST is just the observation that HTTP is good. 
&gt; Neither MoST nor HTTP says anything about the behavior of agents that 
&gt; interact with those resources.
